replies.text:
@fengardice not sure if I follow entirely, is your position

Abolishing prisons is a monumental task, creating a world where white supremacists are actually thrown in prison is also a monumental task. So they're both monumental tasks, and are therefore equally hard to do. So since both are equaly hard to do, we should aim for the one that will do the most good, and that is prison abolition.

or did I misunderstand you?

@mc39785 The conclusion I came to from the video was, "for the most part, we already aren't doing anything about most of them." And more than anything, the current prison system turns people into long term criminals rather than reforming them.

Moreover, the goal of prison and police abolition is to address the societal problems that lead people to do harm in the first place.

And certainly abolitionists are not under the illusion that we will not have dangerous people who we need to protect the public from. I don't really think it's a simple answer though, there might be different solutions depending on the harm, situation, and culture. Self- and community-defense will still be a thing certainly. But nobody can predict what solutions will come up, we can just study how other societies without prisons have handled the issue to get some ideas for how we might do so, which is a much more in depth discussion. But we don't need to have that discussion to see how utterly bad the current system actually is at doing what it claims to do.
